If you don&#39;t support IE11 (or transpile your code anyways), you can get something like that with [tagged template literals](https://exploringjs.com/es6/ch_template-literals.html#_tagged-template-literals):

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    function myjsx(html, ...args) {
      return html.slice(1).reduce((str, elem, i) =&gt; str + args[i] + elem, html[0]);
    }

    var hello = &#39;Hello&#39;;
    var world = &#39;Arcanadian Arc&#39;;
    document.body.innerHTML = myjsx`&lt;h1&gt;${hello} ${world}!&lt;/h1&gt;`;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

There&#39;s even a library that does that: [t7.js](https://www.npmjs.com/package/t7). And there&#39;s a part of the JSX specification draft on why they don&#39;t do that: [Why not template literals](https://facebook.github.io/jsx/#why-not-template-literals).

